<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-181-828  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 181 828.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Feb 1990 v19 n2 p54(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM, committee start drives toward Gbit/s LANs; high-speed LAN mayemploy slot access. (local area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strauss, Paul R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both IBM and the American National Standards Institute (ANSI)X3T9.5 committee that developed the 100M-bit/sec Fiber DistributedData Interface fiber optic local area network (LAN) standard arepursuing higher speed LAN technologies up to the G-bit/sec range.andO;The new IBM LAN has a new access scheme, Cyclic-ReservationMultiple Access (CRMA), and a dual bus that offer up to2.5G-bit/sec performance.andP;  The CRMA scheme uses a slot-reservationtechnique based on an active 'head-end' node (which can be anyselected node) that generates a cycle of 60-byte slots.andP;  The newLAN is capable of distances exceeding 200 Km and the linking ofscores of Ethernet and token-ring LANs.andP;  An ANSI X3T9.5 committeeworking group is reviewing a joint Ascom-Hasler A.G.andP;  (Bern,Switzerland) and In-Net Corp (San Diego, CA) proposal for a dualdata/high-definition television LAN with up to 650M-bit/secperformance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     ANSILocal area networks (Computer networks)PerformanceOptical CommunicationsFuture TechnologiesStandardsFiber Distributed Data Interface Standard.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>